The food here was phenomenal! I had the chocolate chip pancakes, which were every bit as delicious an indulgence as I could have hoped. My husband had the breakfast pizza with broken egg and potato, which I ate a whole slice of and could have eaten more if I hadn’t been so stuffed. Our friends also had delicious dishes, and all of the 3 appetizers we shared were so delicious. We were really impressed with the flavors of all the dishes we tried, and the outdoor seating area was very comfortable and enjoyable. For being an awkward time to be dining out (in the age of COVID), their staff did a great job of making us feel safe and clearly and politely communicating how we could also help keep them safe (such as putting our masks on whenever they came to our table to serve us more things). I’ve never done a brunch where you choose a single entree and then only have bottomless drinks, but it was $10 cheaper than most of the places that offer bottomless dishes as well as drinks around DC and every bit as fun. And since all 4 of us at our table shared our food with each other and ordered some extra apps to start, we still felt like we got to try a lot of different things during the meal. I would highly recommend this place, and I look forward to going back for another brunch again soon!

I love this place so much!  While I've never actually eaten in the downstairs restaurant, I do love me  the Little Coco's pop-up bar upstairs. It's got the makings of all the things I love: strong drinks, ratchet music and laid back vibes.  Although I don't live in this neighborhood, it appears to be a great little spot for those that do. However, it's also well worth the hike across town for someone like me.  My last visit was on a Friday night, a little past the time of traditional happy hour. I was working a little later that I had initially anticipated, but luckily that didn't prevent me from still scoring a few happy hour specials  amidst a healthy crowd - not too packed, but far from empty.  The space upstairs is pretty small, so I was little worried that the quirky, beachy vibes would be insanely popular destination on a summer Friday, but it was the perfect balance for what we were in the mood for.  We only ordered a few snacks (was a big fan of their crispy, stringy fries) and a few concoctions that our bartender, Matt threw down for us. While the company that surrounded me was the tops, Matt really did help us to make the whole evening a fun and memorable one. He was hilarious and still very accommodating and. He cracked us up all night as we all shared our love for the most ratchet hip hop in the land.  Always a good time here and can't wait for the next opportunity to hang here!

Little Coco's is a true neighborhood spot offering yummy food for any meal out of a small building in Petworth. Here's what's to love:  1) Food: It's good. The people behind Little Coco's have a few other top names in the city to their portfolio and the food is consistently good throughout. My friends and I went there for brunch on a Saturday and ordered their version of eggs benedict, French Toast, and the breakfast steak. For only $28, you get any brunch entree with bottomless mimosas (regular and pomegranate) or beer. Every item we ordered was spot on and I'm obsessed with their pomegranate mimosas. The server does an excellent job of making sure your glass is never empty.  2) Portions: For a city know for smaller portions than other parts of the USA (ahem, Middle West), Little Coco's is not conservative. Portion sizes are HUGE. So much so that if you have a group of four, you can order 3 dishes and have everyone leave full.  3) Space: It's beautiful. They have booth seats up front and smaller tables in the back with a bar. The decorations are quirky, but make the space feel casually classy and homey.  Little Coco will make "best brunches in DC' lists no doubt.

When waiters take your order and don't use a notepad, you expect them to remember your order; we had a table for 5 and the waiter came back to take some of our orders a second time because she had forgotten. When the food arrived we were brought the wrong pizza and our waiter seemed confused that we wanted to send it back. Because one of our pizzas was sent back, half of our party ate before the other.  The menu was smaller than expected for a pizza place with only a few house pies listed.  Cocktails were excellent. Food was good once the proper pizzas arrived. Service needs a lot of work.

I had such high hopes for this restaurant. My friends and I visited as a group of 4 for dinner on Saturday 3/10/18 at around 9pm. I looked at the reservations available b4 getting there and saw that there were tables available at 9, however I didn’t reserve since I live 2 min away. When we got there the hostess was so unfriendly we should have probably cut our losses and moved on but we agreed to wait for a table for 1/2hr. During our wait, 20 of the 30+ minuets we waited there were 2 empty tables in plain view. But we patiently waited at the bar without complaint. The bartender was brash and short. Anytime we ordered a drink, it felt like we were bothering her. At the 30 minute mark, I inquired with hostess how much longer our wait would be and her reply was “I said it would be at least 30 minutes. There’s at least in table with a check on it” Utterly rude. I walked back to the bar and about 10 min later she informed us that a table was ready. When I went to sit at the booth, there was a sharp nail sticking out and it scratched my leg pretty badly (it was bleeding and I used my own bandaid). The hostess was standing right there and barely said anything. She leaned in to feel the nail as if I was over exaggerating and still barely said anything resembling an apology. I just let it slide since I was still trying to salvage the experience with my group of friends. The waitress was really awesome. She really tried and we appreciated her for it - she comped us 2 appetizers for the injury caused by the nail. The food was decent as well, except I ordered a vegan pizza, they put cheese on it and then replaced the order. When the bill came, they charged me for 2 pizzas. So we had to ask for one to be removed from the bill. Like I said, really wanted to love this place. But in order to warrant return visits, restaurants must have great service. You can serve the best food in the world, but if you can’t treat your paying customers right, forget it. I won’t spend my money at little coco ever again. And you should think twice about spending yours there too.

Little cocos is a wonderful place for brunch or to go with friends. Very cute place with great food and quaint atmosphere, and though a little expensive it is worth it. Last time I went I got brunch and I got a vegetarian omelet, which was incredible, with home fried potatoes which were also great. My friends got the nutella nut French toast and the lobster omelet - both of which were also great.

I like the pizza at Little Cocos very much. Seemingly, they  use a Mexican type of tomato sauce on their pizza, which I had never tasted on pizza before, but it works. Their blond beer is also very good.
Killer happy hour, $15 draft pitchers, $21 bottles of wine, and fun cocktails.  Food menu has great deals as well.  Loved the burrata.  Outdoor seating available.
The poppyseed cream puffs in the bread basket are spectacular.

Love the food and service! I wish they had more vegetarian items on the menu, but the easier have always been fantastic and accommodating with substitutions.   The cacio e pepe is the best I've ever had!
always great

Little Italian pizza place in Petworth, with a perfectly sized menu and a good, but short, happy hour. More than just pizza, they have all sorts of great Italian antipasti and bites, and some pretty unique entre le options. This place is locavore/farm-to-table friendly, getting most of their produce and meat from the MD and VA area. Eat with confidence!!
Great pizza and cocktails.  Friendly staff

Omg the duck fat cocktail is unbelievable. And the baked eggs are incredible. The waitress remembered me from last time! Awesome service. All in all, the whole package. The kinda of place that will make upper 14th st the next hot neighborhood!
Amazing. Very pleasing atmosphere & food
My child thinks the food is ok
Great little spot in Columbia Heights. Good drafts, solid pizza. Great music during happy hour.
Fantastic pizza.  Sharp interior.
Great food and drink!
Food and service were awesome.
Great lunch combo, beer and pizza for $15!!
Great pizza, great vibe, highly recommended
Great new spot! Will be going back soon.
Nice place. Bar should offer same menu as dining.
Great cocktails, pizza and perfect service.
The duck omelette is where it's at! Also, the staff are super chill, the music is great, and they have a wall of painted album covers dedicated to pizza.  Worth it.
Had a really delicious dinner here the other night. Cool, laid back staff were both helpful with recommendations and attentive.
Great lunch. Huge Amaro selection.
The staff were very friendly and attentive. The atmosphere is welcoming and warm. But the food is average at best
Wonderful addition to the neighborhood. The food has an unexpected polish for the price point, and the drinks are spectacular. Great for date night.
This restaurant is outstanding.  Its in the neighborhood, so we have been a few times.  Never been disappointed or let down by a dish.  Their Cacio e Pepe is really really good.

I'm so happy this place opened nearby. No reservations, so it's nice to be able to walk there and put my name in, although Red Derby and Lyman's are close enough for drinks if you have to wait a while. The booth attached to the bar is definitely the best seat in the house. So far my favorite dishes are the Cacio e Pepe, Brandade Fritters, and the Fools Gold Pizza. Their food is on par with Maple, but Little Coco's is slightly more approachable with the casual interior and price point, so it's nice for random nights out.
Awesome little spot! Wonderful food, great bar

So good! Can't wait to go back! Shared the Eggs Benedetto, Nutella French Toast, and the Fool's Gold Pizza with friends. Also tried the Frozen Bellini and their version of a Dark and Stormy. Everything was really good. Service was excellent and the timing was great too. The restaurant has a nice set-up and a rooftop I look forward to checking out.

Great kitchen. Could use some more greens on the menu to balance the dishes. Great pastas made in house. Want them to look to some ragu to go with them. A definite winner if you're looking for Italian food in Petworth

Good service and overall a nice place. Prices are a bit high for the neighborhood and there are very few vegetarian options. Sure you can hold this or that from a dish, but that's not really the same as a well thought out vegetarian dish.
Food is delicious. Cocktails are great. Vibe is awesome.

This place just made our neighborhood a whole lot nicer. We showed up on opening night before they even had everything sorted out and were blown away still. All the food was delicious and the atmosphere is spot on.  Really great spot for dinner or a drink.
